issue(id="0010" status="open")
  title Support sealed host-sourced auth for clean modules such as gcloud
  user-story
    as-a scrubs VM user relying on clean-space cloud tooling
    i-want tools such as gcloud to arrive with a strong non-interactive clean auth path
    so-that I can use cloud CLIs immediately after bootstrap without reintroducing plaintext guest credentials or weakening the clean/dirty boundary
  premise.
    Scrubs already has a strong motivation for host-sourced clean auth: tools
    that belong to clean space should not force ad hoc guest login ceremony,
    and they should not encourage plaintext token persistence inside the guest.
    That need is not limited to GitHub CLI and Codex. Clean modules such as
    gcloud will also need an opinionated auth path if they are going to feel
    product-ready inside scrubs.

    gcloud is a particularly useful forcing function because its host-side auth
    state is not a single obvious token file. The Cloud SDK can involve
    configuration files, token databases, and application-default-credentials
    material. The right solution therefore is probably not "copy the whole host
    directory blindly," but rather a narrower sealed artifact plus a clean
    wrapper that materializes only the runtime state the target process needs.

    The broader design question is how scrubs should let clean modules opt into
    auth support without mixing secret acquisition into the module definition
    itself. The likely model is that bootstrap owns host discovery and sealing,
    while the clean module or companion wrapper owns runtime materialization.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented policy for extending the sealed clean-auth model to clean modules beyond `gh` and Codex, with gcloud as the first concrete target.
    criterion A fresh guest can use gcloud through a non-interactive clean auth path sourced from the host rather than guest-local login ceremony.
    criterion Any guest-local persisted gcloud auth material is stored only as a sealed artifact or equivalent encrypted form, not as plaintext token files or copied host state.
    criterion Runtime materialization for gcloud occurs only when the clean launch path is invoked, and the materialized plaintext state is scoped narrowly enough that ordinary dirty execution cannot discover or reuse it.
    criterion The chosen design clearly separates module composition, host auth discovery, secret sealing, runtime wrapper behavior, and rotation or revocation guidance.
    criterion At least one validation path demonstrates the intended gcloud behavior end to end, including evidence that clean-space auth works after bootstrap and that dirty execution cannot reach the sealed gcloud auth surface.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether gcloud should consume a sealed minimal config bundle, a
      sealed ADC-style credential artifact, or some other narrower host-sourced
      representation.
    item(status="open").
      Decide how clean modules should declare that they need auth support
      without turning Nix modules into secret-discovery code.
    item(status="open").
      Decide how much host Cloud SDK state is safe and necessary to copy, and
      explicitly exclude caches, logs, or other incidental files that do not
      belong in the guest auth surface.
    item(status="open").
      Make sure the design covers both CLI-shaped usage and application-default
      credential usage where appropriate, without assuming they are the same
      problem.
